Here is a C++ function that takes a reference to a std::string containing markdown formatted text and returns a std::string containing html formatted text:

```cpp
#include <string>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
  std::string html;

  // Iterate through each character in the markdown string
  for(char c : markdown) {

    // Handle markdown formatting
    if(c == '#') {
      // Handle heading
      html += "<h1>";
    } else if(c == '*') {
      // Handle bold/italics
      html += "<b>"; 
    } else {
      // Pass character through unchanged  
      html += c;
    }
  }

  // Close any open tags  
  html += "</h1>";
  html += "</b>";

  return html;
}
```

This function iterates through each character in the markdown string. It checks for specific formatting characters like '#' for headings and '*' for bold/italics. When it finds a formatting character it adds the corresponding HTML opening tag. Regular characters are just passed through unchanged. After iterating it closes any open tags that may have been left open. It returns the converted HTML string.

This is a basic implementation that only handles a subset of markdown formatting. It could be expanded to support more markdown syntax like paragraphs, lists, links etc.

