Here is a function that takes an array of 5 numbers as input and checks if any of the numbers is prime, printing it to the console if so:

```js
function checkForPrime(nums) {
  for (let i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {
    let num = nums[i];
    let isPrime = true;
    if (num < 2) {
      isPrime = false;
    } else {
      for (let j = 2; j < num; j++) {
        if (num % j === 0) {
          isPrime = false;
          break;
        }
      }
    }
    if (isPrime) {
      console.log(num);
    }
  }
}

// Sample usage
let numbers = [3, 15, 7, 12, 23];
checkForPrime(numbers);

// Output: 
// 3
// 7
// 23
```

This function iterates through the array of numbers, checks each one for primality using a basic primality test (division by all integers from 2 to the number itself), and logs any primes to the console.

There are a few ways to narrow down the type in TypeScript when you know more than the type system:

- Use a type assertion:

  ```ts
  const value: unknown = getValue();
  const narrowedValue = value as SpecificType; 
  ```

- Use a user-defined type guard function:

  ```ts 
  function isSpecificType(value: unknown): value is SpecificType {
    // type check logic
    return true;
  }

  if(isSpecificType(value)) {
    // value is SpecificType here
  }
  ```

- Conditional type narrowing:

  ```ts
  type Value = 
    | SpecificType
    | OtherType

  function handleValue(value: Value) {
    if(/* condition */) {
      // value is SpecificType
    } else {
      // value is OtherType
    }
  }
  ```

- Generic type parameter defaults:

  ```ts
  function fn<T extends SpecificType = SpecificType>(value: T) {
    // value is SpecificType
  }

  fn(value);
  ```

So in summary, type assertions, type guards, conditional types and defaults can all help narrow the type when you have additional knowledge beyond what the type system knows.

